  "prompt": "Is GDP a good measure for the standard of living?",
  "response": "GDP (Gross Domestic Product) has both strengths and limitations as a measure of standard of living:\n\nStrengths:\n1. Indicates overall economic output and wealth\n2. Provides a general sense of economic productivity\n3. Allows comparisons between countries and over time\n\nLimitations:\n1. Doesn't account for income distribution\n2. Doesn't measure quality of life or individual well-being\n3. Ignores non-market activities (e.g., household work)\n4. Doesn't reflect environmental sustainability\n5. Doesn't measure access to healthcare, education, or social services\n6. Doesn't capture informal economic activities\n\nBetter alternative measures:\n1. GDP per capita (provides a more nuanced view)\n2. Human Development Index (HDI)\n3. Genuine Progress Indicator (GPI)\n4. Purchasing Power Parity (PPP)\n5. Gini coefficient (measures income inequality)\n\nConclusion:\nGDP can provide insights into economic performance, but it's an imperfect measure of standard of living. A comprehensive assessment requires multiple indicators that capture economic, social, and qualitative aspects of life.",
